<p>The <code>optional</code> function returns the value or empty string if null (null coalescing).</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}echo $sampleText | optional{close}</pre>
<p>Existing value: <b>{echo $sampleText | optional}</b></p>

<pre>{open}echo $undefinedVar | optional{close}</pre>
<p>Undefined (empty): <b>{echo $undefinedVar | optional}</b></p>

<h2>Safe Output</h2>
<p>Use <code>optional</code> to safely output variables that might not exist:</p>
<pre>{open}echo $maybeNull | optional{close}</pre>

<h2>Chained Examples</h2>
<pre>{open}echo $sampleText | optional | trim{close}</pre>
<p>Safe trim: <b>{echo $sampleText | optional | trim}</b></p>

<pre>{open}echo $undefinedVar | optional | trim | upper{close}</pre>
<p>Chain on undefined: <b>{echo $undefinedVar | optional | trim | upper}</b> (empty)</p>

<h2>With Default</h2>
<p>For default values, use conditional logic instead:</p>
<pre>{open}if $value{close}{open}echo $value{close}{open}else{close}default{open}/if{close}</pre>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>The <code>optional</code> function prevents errors when accessing potentially undefined variables. It's similar to PHP's null coalescing operator (<code>??</code>).</p>
